frameDefinitions: This frame concerns Communicators communicating with each other with the aid of a Means of communication such as a telephone.
A Rider is being transported in a Vehicle, or is moving on foot.
Words in this frame describe a relationship in which an Item is expressed through a Text.
A Predicate  is said to apply in a particular Domain.
An Experiencer, Expressor, or State has a feeling of annoyance as evoked by a Stimulus or concerning a Topic.
This frame describes the Impression which a Figure, which can be a person, an organization, or an object, leaves with an Audience.
frameExamples: <t>Mounted</t> police officers are a common sight in this village.
The act of murder is rampant <t>in</t> the Bible.
The Normal College is <t>geographically</t> adjacent to the University of North Wales.
He had an extremely fragile self - <t><fex name='Impression'>image</fex></t>
listRoleDefinitions: This role is the person who uses the <fen>Means</fen> of communication to deliver the <fen>Message</fen> to the Addressee. The Speaker is normally expressed as the External Argument of target verbs, or as the Genitive modifier of  nouns.

<fen>Addressee</fen> is the person to whom the <fen>Message</fen> is communicated. When this role is expressed, it often appears in a prepositional phrase introduced by to, or as the direct object, or as the first object in a double object construction.
This role identifies the content that the <fen>Communicator</fen> communicates to the <fen>Addressee</fen>. It can be expressed as a clause or as a noun phrase.
<fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the <fen>Message</fen> pertains. It is typically expressed as a PP Complement headed by about.

This Frame Element refers to the Instrument of Communication that is used by the <fen>Communicator</fen> (and <fen>Addressee</fen>). Each LU in this frame incorporates the <fen>Means</fen> frame element.
The <fen>Rider</fen> is being transported by a <fen>Vehicle</fen>.
The written source, body of work, or linguistic utterance in which the <fen>Item</fen> is found/expressed.
The piece of information or expression that is contained within the <fen>Text</fen>.
When the <fen>Item</fen> appears in the <fen>Text</fen>.
This Frame Element denotes the <fen>Predicate</fen> which is applied to the <fen>Domain</fen>.
This Frame Element applies to the <fen>Domain</fen> in which the <fen>Predicate</fen> is said to apply.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> is the person or sentient entity that experiences or feels the emotions.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the general area in which the emotion occurs.  It indicates a range of possible <fen>Stimulus</fen>.
The <fen>Stimulus</fen> is the person, event, or state of affairs that evokes the emotional response in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.

The body part, gesture, or other expression of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> that reflects his or her emotional state.  They describe a presentation of the experience or emotion denoted by the adjective or noun.
The <fen>State</fen> is the abstract noun that describes a more lasting experience by the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Experiencer</fen>, <fen>Expressor</fen>, or <fen>State</fen> can be described as having said emotion.
The entity (a person, organization, product, or event) for which the <fen>Audience</fen> has an <fen>Impression</fen>.
A person or group of people who have an <fen>Impression</fen> of a <fen>Figure</fen>.
A generalized conception of a <fen>Figure</fen> presented to or shared by an <fen>Audience</fen>.
listRoleExamples: <fex>The President</fex> cabled his assistant to cancel all of his appointments.
The President cabled <fex>his assistant</fex> to cancel all other engagements.
Britain and France are close , not only <fex>geographically</fex> , but also strategically .
